<problem display_name="Quick Picks" linenum="515" tex_filename="./block1/linearindependence.tex" showanswer="finished" attempts="2" rerandomize="per_student">
  <text>
    <p>
Without doing any row-reduction, you should be able to pick out three of the following lists of vectors that are linearly dependent. Which three? </p>
    <ul class="itemize">
      <li>
        <p>
List A: [mathjaxinline]\left\{  \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{array} \right]; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{array} \right]; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{array} \right] \right\}[/mathjaxinline] </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
List B: [mathjaxinline]\left\{ \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{array} \right] ; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{array} \right] ; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 2 \\ 5 \\ 7 \end{array} \right] \right\}[/mathjaxinline] </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
List C: [mathjaxinline]\left\{ \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \\ 4\end{array} \right] ; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 2 \\ 13 \\ 3 \\ 7\end{array} \right] ; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 0 \\ 1 \\ 5 \\ -3\end{array} \right] ; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 15 \\ -2 \\ 6 \\ 2\end{array} \right] ; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 5 \\ 3 \\ 8 \\ 11\end{array} \right] \right\}[/mathjaxinline] </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
List D: [mathjaxinline]\left\{ \left[ \begin{array}{c} 2 \\ 3 \\ 5 \\ 7 \\ 11 \end{array} \right] ; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \\ 4 \\ 5 \end{array} \right] ; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 2 \\ 4 \\ 6 \\ 8 \\ 10 \end{array} \right] ; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \\ 5 \end{array} \right] \right\}[/mathjaxinline] </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
List E: [mathjaxinline]\left\{ \left[ \begin{array}{c} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0\\ 2 \\ 3 \\ 0 \end{array} \right] ; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 0 \\ 2 \\ 0\\ 7 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{array} \right] ; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 0 \\ 12 \\ 0\\ 23 \\ 35 \\ 0 \end{array} \right] \right\}[/mathjaxinline] </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
List F: [mathjaxinline]\left\{ \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{array} \right] ; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{array} \right] ; \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \\ 2 \end{array} \right] \right\}[/mathjaxinline] </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <choiceresponse>
        <checkboxgroup>
          <choice correct="false" name="1">
            <text>A</text>
          </choice>
          <choice correct="true" name="2">
            <text>B</text>
          </choice>
          <choice correct="true" name="3">
            <text>C</text>
          </choice>
          <choice correct="true" name="4">
            <text>D</text>
          </choice>
          <choice correct="false" name="5">
            <text>E</text>
          </choice>
          <choice correct="false" name="6">
            <text>F</text>
          </choice>
        </checkboxgroup>
      </choiceresponse>
    </p>
    <p>
      <solution>
        <font color="blue">Answer: </font>
        <font color="blue">
          <p>
 Choice B has the zero vector and is therefore linearly dependent. Choice C has 5 vectors in [mathjaxinline]\mathbb R^4[/mathjaxinline] and is therefore linearly dependent (expressed as a matrix, there would be more columns than rows). Choice E has a pair of collinear vectors: the third vector is twice the second vector. The list in choice E is therefore linearly dependent.  </p>
        </font>
      </solution>
    </p>
  </text>
</problem>
